<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / World Trade News: Mexico waits for news from Capitol Hill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Attention has remained firmly fixed throughout the week on the political
machinations which have been taking place on Capitol Hill, Washington.
However, while it was by no means clear earlier yesterday that President
Bill Clinton and his administration had gathered enough votes to ensure that
the North American Free Trade Agreement would win US congress approval, the
Mexican equity market has behaved as though last night's vote was a
formality.
On five successive days Mexico's IPC index has reached record levels. But
data supplied by the IFC tells a slightly different story: the country
recorded a modest gain in dollar terms on the week, its improvement on the
year to date standing at just above 16 per cent, similarly restrained in
comparison to gains elsewhere in the region and the world.
Pakistan, for instance, saw the week's best performance as investors
responded to an improved political climate, while Thailand also moved on.
China and Zimbabwe have been added to the IFC data from this week.
