<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / International Company News: Static third quarter at Thomson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THOMSON Corporation, the Canadian-controlled travel and publishing group,
blamed adverse exchange rates and competitive pressures in several of its
key publishing businesses for near-stagnant third-quarter earnings.
Net earnings edged up to USDollars 226m before preferred share dividends, or
39 cents per common share, from Dollars 221m, or 38 cents a year earlier.
Sales dipped to Dollars 1.86bn from Dollars 1.94bn.
If exchange rates had remained unchanged from average 1992 levels, earnings
would have been 44 cents per share and sales Dollars 2.12bn.
Nine-month earnings rose to Dollars 249m, or 42 cents a share, from Dollars
244m, or 41 cents.
The brightest spot so far this year has been the travel business. Although
UK-based Thomson Travel's nine-month operating profit dipped to Dollars 143m
from Dollars 146m, the company said there was an 18.6 per cent jump measured
in sterling.
Thomson Tours' volumes rose 11 per cent last summer, and sales of winter
holidays are 16 per cent ahead of last year.
The company said summer 1994 bookings have been 'exceptionally high' since
its brochures were launched in late August, leading to a 'significant'
improvement in market share.
An official ascribed the improvement to a stronger UK economy and last
summer's poor weather, which has encouraged many people to book a holiday in
the sun.
In the publishing and newspaper divisions, there were poor performances by
the UK and US professional, business and academic publishing groups, and
Thomson's Canadian newspaper chain. But UK regional newspapers' operating
profits were well ahead.
</TEXT>
