<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / International Company News: Nutricia warns of food recall
damage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Nutricia, one of Europe's largest producers of baby food, fell
sharply yesterday after a warning that a recall of 1m jars of baby food
would affect its profit forecast for 1993. It could also influence results
in 1994, the company cautioned.
Nutricia, a Dutch-based company 30 per cent-owned by Unigate of the UK, is
recalling some lines of its Olvarit brand of baby food because jars
containing pork and beef may contain traces of a disinfectant. The recall
affects jars in the Netherlands, Belgium, Greece and Portugal.
More than 1m jars of the food still stored in Nutricia's warehouses will
also be destroyed.
Nutricia's shares fell steeply on the Amsterdam stock exchange yesterday,
closing down Fl 13.20, or 8.7 per cent, at Fl 138.20. In London, Unigate's
shares ended the day down 12p at 355p.
Nutricia, the biggest European baby food producer after Nestle of
Switzerland, said the source of the disinfectant was not its own Olvarit
factory in Wells, England, but the premises of one of its Dutch suppliers of
pork and beef. The disinfectant, p-TSA, is used to clean meat-cutting tables
and equipment.
The Olvarit jars were recalled after traces of the disinfectant were found
during a routine check in the Netherlands by Dutch food inspectors. Olvarit
products without meat, or with other types of meat, were not included in the
recall.
The company said there was no danger to health unless the suspect food was
eaten frequently and over a long period.
The company said the recall would affect its profit forecast for 1993, which
earlier called for a 'clear' increase from 1992 net profit of Fl 87.2m
(Dollars 30.7m). Meals, drinks and cereals for babies and toddlers accounted
for around 16 per cent of Nutricia's 1992 sales of Fl 1.25bn.
</TEXT>
