<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Land Securities edges ahead to Pounds
118.9m - Pounds 2.9m boost from sale of investment properties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAND SECURITIES, the UK's biggest property company, yesterday lifted its
interim dividend as pre-tax profits edged ahead to Pounds 118.9m for the six
months to the end of September.
The outcome compared with a previous Pounds 116.5m. Earnings per share were
ahead from 16.58p to 17.22p; the dividend is lifted by 4.8 per cent from
6.3p to 6.6p.
Excluding the Pounds 2.9m proceeds on the sale of investment properties,
pre-tax profit was almost unchanged at Pounds 116m (Pounds 116.2m). Net
rental income improved from Pounds 187.6m to Pounds 192m.
Mr Peter Hunt, chairman and managing director, said the results confirmed
his view that, until rental growth fed through into higher rents, net
revenue from the group's existing portfolio was likely to remain flat.
He described the recovery as slow and fragile. Rents were continuing to fall
in central London, but increased enquiries and a falling level of high
quality space suggested that 'rental levels for the best property may be
close to reaching a floor.'
The group, which in May raised Pounds 140m for new property investment
through a convertible bond issue, spent or committed Pounds 70m on purchases
during the six months. The biggest purchase was the Bridges Shopping Centre
in Sunderland. At the end of September it had just over Pounds 295m of funds
available for future acquisitions, developments and refurbishments.
Net interest payable rose from Pounds 59m to Pounds 65.1m.
Mr Hunt said the group had made considerable progress in reducing voids from
about 4 per cent of the rent roll to 3 per cent, excluding vacant buildings
held for future development.
The group would continue its policy of cutting the level of voids and
overheads, rebalancing its portfolio with retail and industrial/warehouse
acquisitions, and keeping its property in the best possible condition.
</TEXT>
