<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Rover loses instigator of revival - The
large vacuum at the top left by George Simpson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTURE of Mr George Simpson from British Aerospace to become chief
executive of Lucas leaves a large gap at the top of Rover group, BAe's motor
vehicles subsidiary.
The emergence of Rover as one of the more unlikely success stories of the
European motor industry in the last couple of years has owed much to Mr
Simpson's leadership.
He has been instrumental in driving forward the strategy of so-called -
moving the former chronically loss-making, state-owned carmaker increasingly
up-market into more lucrative segments dominated by producers such as BMW
and away from the dogfight of the volume carmakers.
The architect of this bold marketing strategy for the transformation of the
old, ailing British Leyland volume carmaker into an market manufacturer of
executive cars, was Sir Graham Day, Mr Simpson's predecessor as Rover group
chairman and the man responsible for returning Rover, then BL, to the
private sector in 1988 with its takeover by British Aerospace.
Sir Graham picked Mr Simpson to put the strategy into action, however, when
he appointed him managing director in 1988, and since 1991 he has been both
Rover chairman and chief executive.
The decision to leave Rover has not been an easy one. Mr Simpson, a Scottish
accountant, has been in the motor industry for most of his career, and
virtually all of this time since 1969 has been spent with Rover in its
various earlier guises as BLMC, British Leyland or BL.
Among his earlier posts he was variously managing director of Coventry
Climax, of Freight Rover (BL's van operations), and of Leyland Trucks. He
became chief executive of Leyland Daf, when the BL truck operations were
taken over by Daf of the Netherlands in 1987 but was brought back to Rover
only a year later.
After all the years of frustration, decline and restructuring the ugly
duckling of BL is fast becoming a swan in the shape of Rover. Mr Simpson has
had to weigh up the chances of possibly leading Rover into some form of
independence, if BAe should choose to cash in and float off the car-making
operations at an opportune moment. The carrot dangled by Lucas was the
certain opportunity to head a leading UK manufacturing group now, removing
any uncertainty posed by the vagaries of BAe's corporate manoeuvres.
Mr Simpson leaves Rover in better shape than it has been for decades. The
management team led by Mr John Towers, group managing director, and now
BAe's most senior Rover executive, inherits an operation that is moving
sharply back into profit this year in vivid contrast with most of the
European motor industry that is slipping steeply into loss.
Rover group is the only significant carmaker in Europe to have increased its
sales volume this year helped by the increase in the UK market and a strong
performance - albeit from a small base - in the contracting markets of
Germany, Italy and France. Its sales in west Europe have jumped by 12.9 per
cent in a market that has fallen by 15.3 per cent. Its sales of four-wheel
drive Land Rover vehicles have been growing strongly, and - amidst the
swathes of job cuts in the European auto industry - Land Rover has been
adding jobs.
Rover will be in profit for the full year in 1993 after two years of losses,
says Mr Simpson. In the first six months Rover cut its operating loss before
interest to Pounds 19m from Pounds 31m in the corresponding period last
year.
The first half loss included redundancy and restructuring costs of Pounds
22m. Excluding the one-off rationalisation charge Rover's trading
performance in the first six months improved by Pounds 34m from a year ago
and already resulted in a small profit of Pounds 3m.
Rover has forecast 'a significant recovery' in its financial performance in
the second half of this year.
Production, which fell by 6.4 per cent to 200,872 in the first half under
the impact of significant stock reductions, has risen significantly in the
second half. The benefits from last year's devaluation of sterling, which
were delayed by currency hedging arrangements, are also being fully
reflected in the second half.
The UK car maker's first half financial performance was impaired by launch
costs of around Pounds 10m for the new Rover 600 executive car, which was
introduced in April.
In the second half Rover has benefitted from strong UK sales in August, when
its registrations increased by 23.7 per cent in an overall market, which
rose by 17.8 per cent.
The group has increased its market share in the UK and profitability is
being helped by an improving 'model mix' with an increasing proportion of
sales coming from its larger Rover cars and fourwheel drive Land Rover
vehicles.
</TEXT>
