<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Wider powers for DTI in deregulation bill: Government aims
to repeal 'hundreds' of measures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Trade and Industry is to receive sweeping new powers
enabling it to repeal hundreds of regulatory measures without having to
refer to parliament.
The new powers will be contained in a deregulation bill, to be announced in
today's Queen's Speech.
While the details of the bill will remain under wraps until later next
month, Mr Neil Hamilton, minister of corporate affairs, said the government
planned to get rid of 'hundreds of regulations' without seeking primary
legislation.
In a recent interview with the Financial Times, Mr Hamilton, who is
spearheading the government's deregulation initiative, said: 'We are
planning to clear out the accumulated dross of a number of bills without
seeking primary legislation which would clog up parliament.'
He made it clear that the DTI would have new powers to repeal by order many
statutory instruments, which allow ministers to make regulations without the
specific order of parliament.
Mr Hamilton was scathing about many of the country's 'mushrooming
regulations', which he said had become an intolerable burden on bus-iness.
The minister plans to use the new powers to roll back the boundaries of
regulation, although he has not yet decided which specific regulations will
be repealed.
But he made it clear that he is prepared to question all red tape by
singling out the Financial Services Act, which underpins City regulation. He
said it had given rise to many non-statutory rules.
In response to well-publicised fraud cases in the 1980s, Mr Hamilton said
the government was criticised by parliament for not being 'draconian enough'
in cracking down on insider dealing. So it had introduced more regulation in
the form of the FSA.
'This goes to the heart of the problem,' he said. 'You either take a
proportionalist or absolutist view of how to deal with problems.'
Mr Hamilton said he was aware that much of what he was proposing was
controversial, but said it was essential that somebody asked difficult
questions. 'In the past there has been no scientific method of opposing
regulation.'
A series of seven business taskforces is busy identifying regulations that
could be scrapped after the contents of the deregulation bill are published.
The bill will also ensure that before new legislation is introduced,
ministers will be forced to complete what Mr Hamilton called a compliance
cost assessment - how much it will cost industry and small businesses.
Mr Hamilton said he would not allow what he called the 'Sir Humphrey
syndrome' in Whitehall to cause his initiative to run into the sands.
</TEXT>
<XX>
