<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Pay rises at 15-year low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE ARE no signs of an upturn in the rate of wage increases and
productivity is continuing to improve, according to the Confederation of
British Industry's pay databank series for the third quarter of the year,
published yesterday.
Increases in pay for the January-September period were on average 2.3 per
cent, the lowest level recorded by the CBI since it started collecting pay
data in 1977.
Pay deals in manufacturing averaged 2.3 per cent, down from 3.9 per cent for
the same period last year. There was a rise of 2.6 per cent in the private
services sector, compared with 4.3 per cent.
Mr Howard Davies, the CBI's director-general, said yesterday: 'These figures
are generally encouraging, showing that the need for tighter control of pay
remains well understood by employers and their workforces.'
The CBI added that the databank findings meant 'continued good news for
British competitiveness' with reported provisional productivity gains in
manufacturing running at 3.9 per cent, well ahead of wage settlements.
The overall third quarter CBI pay figures compare with a 3.9 per cent
provisional figure for the same period last year and 2.3 per cent for the
second quarter of this year.
The CBI said that one in five pay deals in the manufacturing and services
sectors involved wage freezes.
</TEXT>
