<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Six tender for Pounds 300m London-Heathrow link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH, German, French and Japanese companies are among six bidders for the
main tunnelling contracts for the Pounds 300m Paddington to Heathrow rail
link.
The privately financed scheme is to be built by a joint venture between BAA,
which runs Heathrow airport, and British Rail. Japan's Export Import Bank
recently agreed a loan facility of up to Pounds 135m to help finance the
project.
The tunnelling works will be the main cost. Taylor Woodrow, the UK
contractor, has been appointed overall construction manager for the 25km
line.
The tender list for the tunnelling works comprises Balfour Beatty from the
UK and five joint ventures involving UK and overseas companies:
Amec, with Hochtief (Germany);
Sir Robert McAlpine, Taylor Woodrow, Wayss &amp; Freytag (Germany) and Bachy
(France);
Miller, Tarmac, Kumagai Gumi (Japan) and BEMO-NATM (Austria);
Kier, Murphy and Kunz (Germany);
Nuttall, Trafalgar House and Zublin (Germany).
The works involve constructing escalator and lift shafts as well as driving
two 2.95km tunnels from north of the M4 to underground stations connecting
to terminals 1, 2, and 3 at Heathrow. A further 3.2km single track tunnel
will connect with Terminal 4.
Tunnelling for railway stations is highly specialised and only a small
number of British and international companies have the necessary expertise.
</TEXT>
