<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / House sales slow ahead of Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POTENTIAL house purchasers are delaying purchases ahead of this month's
Budget, causing a slowdown in activity in the housing market, says a survey
of more than 100 estate agents in England and Wales published today, Andrew
Taylor writes.
The survey by the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors says there is a
shortage of properties being put up for sale. But buyers are snapping up
homes when they are keenly priced. Almost 90 per cent of agents questioned
last month said prices had remained unchanged over the previous three
months. Only 3.7 per cent reported price rises while 8.7 per cent said
prices were still falling.
The institution said the Budget was casting a shadow over the market with
buyers and sellers concerned that Mr Kenneth Clarke's measures might
undermine confidence.
Estate agents and housebuilders are concerned that Mr Clarke should not
announce further reductions in mortgage tax relief. The rate of relief is
due to fall from 25 per cent to 20 per cent next April.
</TEXT>
