<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Eggar backs market forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG restatement of the government's determination to allow market
forces to rule in the energy market was given yesterday by Mr Tim Eggar, the
energy minister.
He said the government wanted to ensure that people and businesses got the
energy they wanted at competitive prices. 'This is achieved most efficiently
and effectively through competitive markets, which expose real costs and
lead to keenest pricing.'
He speech comes when the government is addressing issues such as the
monopoly in the gas market and the future of nuclear power. The only hint Mr
Eggar gave of these issues was when he referred to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission's recent recommendation to break up British Gas.
He made no reference to the state-owned nuclear power industry whose future
will soon be decided in a government review.
Mr Eggar's speech coincided with a plea from Mr James Hann, the chairman of
Scottish Nuclear, that the government cast the review in wide terms.
'As far as we can judge the key question, if not the only question in
ministers' minds for the forthcoming nuclear review, is whether and on what
basis our industry might be privatisable,' he told a Financial Times
conference on world electricity in London yesterday. He added: 'I regard
this attitude with concern.'
</TEXT>
