<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / 'Sophisticated' Pounds 100m fraud deceived banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHAIRMAN of Wallace Smith Trust Company, the collapsed London merchant
bank, swindled about Pounds 100m from other banks in a sophisticated fraud
which deceived both the Bank of England and Deloitte Haskin &amp; Sells, the
bank's auditors, the Old Bailey was told yesterday.
Mr Wallace Duncan Smith used and re-used certificates of deposit to obtain
loans for several million pounds from different banks, said Mr Timothy
Barnes QC, prosecuting for the Serious Fraud Office.
Mr Smith also defrauded the Discount Bank and Trust Company of Dollars 37m
(Pounds 25m) by entering into 'repo' transactions with the bank using
non-existent Canadian bonds.
The bank lost all the money when Wallace Smith Trust collapsed in 1991 owing
Pounds 100m, Mr Barnes said.
Mr Smith denies two charges of obtaining the Dollars 37m by deception, three
charges of the theft of certificates of deposit worth Pounds 4m, two charges
of false accounting and one charge of fraudulent trading with intent to
defraud creditors.
By 1990 the merchant bank had started to run into financial problems, Mr
Barnes said. To keep trading, Mr Smith, who was also joint managing
director, raised funds by illegally using the same certificates of deposit
as security for further loans from institutions including Life Assurance of
Scotland.
Much of the money was then routed into two shell companies in Canada
operated by Mr Smith. He claimed these companies had substantial assets in
the form of land, oil and gas interests, and a wide-ranging portfolio of
shares.
Both companies were complete shams, Mr Barnes said. They had no assets,
operated out of one-room offices and employed no staff. Nevertheless, the
Wallace Smith Trust charged substantial fees to the Canadian companies for
investment advice and other services.
'To both the Bank of England and Deloitte, it appeared that the bank was
properly managed by people of integrity, was trading profitably and had
substantial capital behind it,' Mr Barnes said.
By late 1990 senior staff within Wallace Smith Trust were challenging Mr
Smith about his methods. But in April 1991 he carried out the largest single
fraud, raising Dollars 37m from Discount Bank using the bogus Canadian
bonds.
In April 1991, however, the bank's senior staff, led by Mr Michael Hamilton,
its other joint managing director, challenged Mr Smith to prove the
existence of the bonds, Mr Barnes said. When he was unable to do so they
prompted Mr Smith to go to the Bank of England. Mr Smith was arrested and
the bank liquidated within two days.
The trial, expected to last several months, continues.
</TEXT>
