<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Salmon farmers angered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH salmon farmers yesterday expressed dismay at the response of the
government to the crisis in the salmon industry, where a surge in production
of salmon by Norway has led to a 60 per cent fall in prices.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, has written to the European Commission
urging 'appropriate measures' to deal with the problems of Scottish salmon
producers.
But he did not request 'safeguard action' under which the Commission would
be obliged to consider measures to restrict imports of Norwegian salmon,
such as setting a minimum import price or limiting volumes that can be
imported.
Mr Lang's more modest request for 'appropriate measures' is believed to be
the result of the Scottish Office and the Ministry of Agriculture being
overruled by Treasury ministers, who oppose trade protection measures.
The Scottish Office said yesterday that since the Irish Republic, another
salmon producer, had already requested safeguard action, a further request
was not needed.
</TEXT>
