<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Puzzle over two Nadir witnesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
QUESTIONS continue to surround the credibility of the two witnesses who
claim to have been behind allegations that Mr Asil Nadir, the fugitive
businessman, attempted to bribe his trial judge.
A number of doubts remain as the attorney general yesterday rejected calls
for a public inquiry into the conduct of the police investigation into the
allegations. The calls were repeated yesterday by Mr Nadir, Mr Michael Mates
MP, and Mr Anthony Scrivener, Mr Nadir's barrister.
In a statement released on Tuesday the Crown Prosecution Service confirmed
that Mr Michael Francis and Ms Wendy Welsher had triggered the original
police investigation.
Mr Francis has a criminal record. Ms Welsher is known to have handled a
valuable painting claimed by Mr Nadir's trustee in bankruptcy. Both are now
believed to be in northern Cyprus, where Mr Nadir fled after illegally
jumping bail in May.
Officials involved in the case yesterday questioned why the two witnesses
were now staying so close to Mr Nadir if they had - as they now claim -
fabricated the evidence to support suggestions that he had attempted to
bribe Mr Justice Tucker.
If the witnesses did make up the evidence - which they now allege was done
at the prompting of senior police officials - they could face severe
penalties for perverting the course of justice.
The police have rejected any suggestions that they were involved in such a
conspiracy. One possible motive for their alleged involvement would be that
the Serious Fraud Office believed Mr Justice Tucker was too sympathetic to
Mr Nadir.
It was Mr Nadir, however, who appealed to the divisional court to change the
judge in March this year in response to concerns that his trial may have
been prejudiced by the allegations.
The original allegations of a conspiracy to pervert the course of justice
were first made in open court during a hearing on Mr Nadir's case in
November last year by Mr Robert Owen QC on behalf of the Serious Fraud
Office.
The investigation was taken up by the Metropolitan Police which, according
to the Crown Prosecution Service, delivered a report on November 5 this year
which contained no 'credible' evidence to support the allegations.
Documents circulated by Mr Nadir during the summer reproduce what is claimed
to be the only evidence of the conspiracy, a piece of paper signed by Safiye
Nadir, Mr Nadir's mother, and Bilge Nevzat, his sister, agreeing to
guarantee payment of Pounds 3.5m to Mr David Kent, a pseudonym for Mr
Francis.
This is supported by a letter saying the SFO was notified of the document on
October 1 1992, with allegations that the money was to be paid to Mr Justice
Tucker following Mr Nadir's successful departure from the UK.
One question for the police - emphasised by both Mr Scrivener and Mr Nadir
yesterday - is whether this was sufficient to justify making the allegations
in court.
</TEXT>
