FT  18 NOV 93 / Vauxhall's joint union deal may go
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VAUXHALL, the motor manufacturer, is threatening to abandon its joint
negotiating agreement with unions and introduce a single union deal for its
9,000 manual workers.
The company is furious at the decision taken by the TGWU general union
locally to start an overtime ban from today at the company's Ellesmere Port
plant on Merseyside.
Postal voting has not yet been completed among Vauxhall's manual workers at
Luton - nor among members of the AEEU engineering and electrical union at
Ellesmere Port, where the TGWU held its ballot earlier.
The unions are balloting members on whether they would back industrial
action against the company's two-year 'final' pay offer of 2.5 per cent this
autumn with a further 3.0 per cent plus 1 per cent lump sum in September
1994.
In a letter sent earlier this week to the TGWU's regional office on
Merseyside, Mr Bruce Warman, Vauxhall personnel director, said that the
union's unilateral action suggested that it wanted to abandon the joint
union machinery.
Mr Warman said: 'If it is your intention that from now on separate union
groups at each of our locations will take industrial action unilaterally
without any co-ordinated or formal response to Vauxhall through the joint
negotiating committee, then we on the management side must seriously
question the role and need for a joint negotiating committee.'
He added: 'Recent actions would indicate that it is not your intention to
follow joint negotiating committee procedures in future and therefore it can
only be assumed that you wish this structure to be disbanded.'
