<DATE>931118
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Pact ushers in government of national unity: New
constitution at a glance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
POWER-SHARING
There will be a government of national unity, with a cabinet composed of all
parties winning more than 5 per cent of the national vote, allocated seats
proportionately. The president will be elected by the national assembly. The
first deputy president, who will act as prime minister, will come from the
majority party; there will be a second deputy president from the second
largest party (probably the National Party). Cabinet decisions will be by
consensus but where impossible, the president's view will prevail. The
principle of a government of national unity cannot be changed until 1999.
REGIONAL POWERS
The constitution provides for significant devolution of power to provincial
governments in areas such as education, health, welfare, policing, etc, but
central government reserves powers to intervene to impose uniform national
standards, to regulate provincial activities and where national economic
policy or security is affected. Provincial governments can impose no taxes
without national assembly approval though they will be guaranteed a share of
national revenue.
PARLIAMENT
Parliament will write a new constitution to replace yesterday's interim
constitution, and act simultaneously as the first non-racial legislature.
There will be two houses: a 400-member national assembly elected by
proportional representation from a party list, with half the representatives
from a national list and half from regional lists. In addition, there will
be a senate composed of 10 members from each of the 9 provinces, elected by
members of the provincial legislatures. When acting as a constituent
assembly, parliament will take decisions by two thirds majority and will be
constrained by constitutional principles set out in the interim
constitution. If the constituent assembly cannot agree by two thirds
majority within two years, there will be a referendum requiring a 60 per
cent vote. If this is not achieved the constituent assembly will continue
seeking agreement for a further three years with a 60 per cent majority
required. When acting as a legislature, a simple majority suffices though
constitutional amendments and bills affecting the powers of provincial
governments must pass by a two thirds majority of both houses.
PROVINCIAL LEGISLATURES
Elections will be held simultaneously for provincial assemblies of 30-100
members elected by proportional representation from a party list. Provincial
assemblies may write a constitution for each province.
BILL OF RIGHTS
Fundamental human rights will be protected under an interim bill of rights
which permits, though it does not enforce, affirmative action and promises
'just and equitable' compensation in the event of expropriation of property.
Compensation disputes will be settled by the courts, taking into account
market value of property, its use and the history of its acquisition.
CONSTITUTIONAL PRINCIPLES
Enshrine basic principles under which the new constitution must be written:
these include independence of the judiciary, devolution of power to
provincincial government, and basic human rights.
LANGUAGE
South Africa is to have 11 official languages, but in practice English is
likely to be the language of government.
LOCAL GOVERNMENT
Local government will be transformed more slowly than national government.
Local negotiating forums or 'councils of local unity' will oversee the
two-year transition to local government elections, with the rights of
property owners even after elections protected by a formula which ensures
that whites will have disproportionate representation.
CIVIL SERVICE
Pensions of civil servants will be protected in exchange for a deal to bring
blacks into the top echelons.
</TEXT>
